A 14-year-old student from Kinshasa is making a name for himself as a budding architect by building miniature models of football stadiums from all over the world and also from his home country. Jorkiam Samba Mampuya, known as Djodjo, is the eldest of five children and hopes to join the ranks of the world's greatest 
architects one day. "I want the world to know me and that I be counted among the great 
architects of this world ... this Congolese who makes great works," 
he said. Who Owns Football? Large football clubs are being bought by foreign businessmen, who some say are only in it for the money with no tie to football history. But a protest movement is taking matters into its own hands to tackle the issues facing Europe's biggest sport.